      "text": "Understood. The user\u0027s feedback provides a crucial clarification of aesthetic preference. The previous implementation was a literal interpretation of the plan, but the user is reacting against the fundamental \"card\" metaphor itself. The new inspiration (`le-samuel`) points towards a more immersive, editorial, and less containerized layout.\n\nA re-evaluation has been completed based on this new directive.\n\n---\n\n### **Phase 1: Re-evaluation and Audit**\n\n**1. Analysis of New Inspiration (`/le-samuel/`)**\nThe user\u0027s preference is now clear. The design of the \"Le Samuel\" page is successful because it rejects containment.\n\n*   **Design Philosophy:** It is an immersive, full-width, \"story-scroll\" experience.\n*   **Layout:** It uses alternating, edge-to-edge sections. A massive, beautiful image is followed by a clean, spacious text block on a plain white background.\n*   **Effect:** This creates a cinematic and premium feel. It does not feel like a list of components on a page; the page *is* the experience. The user\u0027s dislike of the \"grey under the photos\" and the \"raising card\" is a dislike of the visual boxes that break this immersive flow.\n\n**2. Audit of Previous Recommendations Implementation**\n\nThe previous recommendations were implemented, but the core *aesthetic framework* in which they were placed is what the user finds unsatisfactory.\n\n*   **Implemented:**\n    *   Curated collection headline: Yes.\n    *   Host introduction: Yes.\n    *   Guest testimonials on cards: Yes.\n    *   Featured/larger first property: Yes.\n    *   On-hover motion (raising card): Yes. **This is the feature the user explicitly dislikes.**\n\n*   **Conclusion:** The content strategy was successful, but the visual execution (the card metaphor) was the point of failure. The goal now is to re-platform the successful content into a new, user-preferred visual structure.\n\n---\n\n### **Phase 2: Council Debate Synthesis**\n\n*   The **Cultural Guardian** notes: \"The user doesn\u0027t want a gallery of framed pictures; they want a walk-through film. We need to shift from \u0027presenting\u0027 properties to \u0027enveloping\u0027 the user within them, one after another.\"\n*   The **Civic Guardian** adds: \"The \u0027Le Samuel\u0027 layout feels more bespoke and high-end. Removing the generic card containers elevates the perceived value of each property by giving it its own unique space on the page.\"\n*   The **Technical Guardian** advises: \"This is a structural CSS change. We will move from a component-based style (`.property-card`) to a section-based one (`.property-showcase-section`). For the header, we will use a JavaScript scroll listener to add a `.scrolled` class to the header element, triggering a CSS transition to a smaller height. The ProcessWire instructions are straightforward.\"\n*   The **Contrarian Guardian** warns: \"A purely alternating layout of massive-image/text-block for a dozen properties could create its own form of visual fatigue. We must ensure the text blocks have enough internal variety (quotes, lists, buttons) to keep the scroll engaging.\"\n\n---\n\n### **Phase 3: The New Plan: Precise Instructions**\n\n#### **Instruction 1: Deconstruct the Card into a Full-Width \"Featurette\" Section**\n\nThe primary directive is to **eliminate the card metaphor entirely.** Each property on the showcase page should be treated as a mini landing page section.\n\n1.  **Remove Card Containers:** Delete the wrapper `\u003cdiv\u003e` that creates the card, its background color, box-shadow, and hover effects. The page background should be a simple, clean white.\n2.  **Enlarge and Overlay Image:**\n    *   The property image should now span the full width of the content area (or the full browser viewport, for a more dramatic effect).\n    *   Move the property\u0027s name (`H2` title) to be **overlaid** on the bottom of the image.\n    *   To ensure readability, place a subtle, dark gradient \"scrim\" behind the text, fading from transparent at the top to 30-40% black at the bottom of the image.\n3.  **Create a Clean Content Block:**\n    *   Below the full-width image, create a well-padded content block on the plain white background.\n    *   This block will contain the elements that were previously inside the card: the guest testimonial, the description text, the list of amenities (beds, baths), and the \"Book Now / View\" button. This directly addresses the dislike for the \"grey under the photo.\"\n\nThis new structure should be repeated for each property, creating a flowing, editorial-style page.\n\n#### **Instruction 2: Implement the Shrinking (\"Sticky\") Header on Scroll**\n\n1.  **Default State (Top of page):** The header should have its current, larger height.\n2.  **Scrolled State (After scrolling down ~150px):**\n    *   The header should smoothly transition to a thinner height (e.g., from `120px` to `70px`).\n    *   The following elements **must remain visible**:\n        *   Logo (it may need to be slightly smaller).\n        *   Hamburger menu icon.\n        *   \"Book Now\" button.\n    *   **Add the new element:** The phone number, styled as plain text or a clickable link, should be visible in the scrolled state. Example: `Jay (514) 555-5555`.\n3.  **ProcessWire Requirement:** The phone number string must not be hard-coded in the template. It should be pulled from a global settings field in the ProcessWire admin panel.\n\n#### **Instruction 3: Define Global Site Settings for ProcessWire**\n\nTo empower the site owner and reduce developer dependency, create a \"Site Settings\" or \"Global Content\" page in the ProcessWire admin with the following editable fields. This centralizes recurring information.\n\n| Field Name | Field Type | Purpose | Example |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **`contact_phone_number`** | Text | The main contact number for the sticky header and footer. | `Jay (514) 555-5555` |\n| **`contact_email`** | Email | The primary email address for inquiries. | `contact@icantwait.ca` |\n| **`main_booking_url`** | URL | The default URL for the main \"Book Now\" buttons. | `https://book.someplatform.com/` |\n| **`host_introduction_text`** | Text Area | The introductory paragraph about the host used on the showcase page. | `\"I\u0027m Jay, and I\u0027ve personally selected...\"` |\n| **`host_photo`** | Image | The portrait image of the host. | `jay-portrait.jpg` |\n| **`default_seo_title`** | Text | The default title tag for the site homepage. | `iCantWait.ca - Hand-Picked Montreal Stays` |\n| **`default_seo_description`** | Text Area | The default meta description for search engines. | `\"Discover our curated collection of beautiful, fully-equipped apartments...\"` |",
